title="Linear Algebra Done Right">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> 1.1</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>We define the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Set of Complex Numbers</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}=\{(x,y)\mid  x,y\in \mathbb {R}\}]]></fr:tex>. Given a complex number <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z=(x,y)]]></fr:tex>, we call <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Re (z)=x]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Real Part</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Im (z)=y]]></fr:tex> the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Imaginary Part</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathrm {i}=(0,1)]]></fr:tex> for the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Imaginary Unit</html:dfn> and write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z=(x,y)]]></fr:tex> as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z=x+\mathrm {i} y]]></fr:tex>. (Electrical Engineers use <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[j]]></fr:tex> instead for the imaginary unit.)</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
