title="Linear Algebra Done Right">Linear Algebra Done Right</fr:link> Theorem 1.3</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z_{1},z_{2},z_{3}\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> be complex numbers. Then the following all hold:</fr:p><fr:ol><fr:li>Associativity: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[(z_{1}+z_{2})+z_{3}=z_{1}+(z_{2}+z_{3})]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Commutativity: <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z_{1}+z_{2}=z_{2}+z_{1}]]></fr:tex></fr:li>
<fr:li>Additive identity: There is a unique complex number denoted <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0]]></fr:tex> such that for any <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> we have <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0+z=z]]></fr:tex>. Moreover, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[0=(0,0)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li>
<fr:li>Additive inverse: For each <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z\in \mathbb {C}]]></fr:tex> there exists a unique complex number denoted <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-z]]></fr:tex> such that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z+(-z)=0]]></fr:tex>. Moreover, if <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[z=(x,y)]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[-z=(-x,-y)]]></fr:tex>.</fr:li></fr:ol></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree><fr:tree
